    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>July 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1878</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I write one line to acknowledge your letter &amp; to thank you for all your extraordinary kindness.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I have written to Prof. Flower with all particulars, &amp; urged him to examine carefully the wings.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I suspect that it is near his holidays, when he leaves London, so there may be some delay in the investigation.— You shall hear hereafter.</p>
<p>In Haste | Dear Sir | yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>           
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD misdated his letter 4 July instead of 4 August 1878. This letter is a reply to the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11614.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. A. Blair, 17 July 1878</ref>, which arrived on 4 August (see n. 3, below). </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11614.xml">letter from R. A. Blair, 17 July 1878</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11640.xml">letter to W. H. Flower, 4 [August] 1878</ref> and n. 1.</note>
        </div>
        
    
        
